  1. Copilot Answer

    In the context of databases, TCL (Transaction Control Language) is a subset of SQL commands used to manage transactions in a relational database. Transactions are sequences of operations performed as a single logical unit of work, ensuring data integrity and consistency.

    Key TCL Commands:

    1. COMMIT:
      • Saves all changes made during the current transaction permanently to the database.
      • Example:
        COMMIT;
    1. ROLLBACK:
      • Reverts all changes made during the current transaction, restoring the database to its previous state.
      • Example:
        ROLLBACK;
    1. SAVEPOINT:
      • Creates a point within a transaction to which you can later roll back without affecting the entire transaction.
      • Example:
        SAVEPOINT savepoint_name;
    1. SET TRANSACTION:
      • Configures the properties of a transaction, such as isolation level.
      • Example:
        SET TRANSACTION READ ONLY;

    Use Case:

    TCL commands are essential for ensuring atomicity and consistency in database operations. For example, in a banking system, transferring money between accounts involves multiple steps. If one step fails, a ROLLBACK ensures no partial changes are saved, maintaining data integrity.

    These commands are particularly useful in multi-user environments where concurrent transactions occur.
